A civil engineer involved in construction requires 4800 m3, 5800 m3, and 5700 m3 of sand, fine gravel, and coarse gravel, respectively, for a building project. There are three pits from which these materials can be obtained. The composition of these pits is as follows:

Pit1 55 30 15
Pit2 25 45 30
Pit3 25 20 55

 

How many cubic meters must be hauled from each pit in order to meet the engineer’s needs? (Round the final answers to one decimal places.)

 

The solutions are as follows.

 

  x (m3)
Pit1 __a__
Pit2 __b__
Pit3 __c__

%media:formula36.mml%

clear, clc
A=[0.55 0.25 0.25;0.3 0.45 0.20;0.15 0.30 0.55];

Components Metal (g/component) Plastic (g/component) Rubber (g/component)

2 17 0.40 1.2

If totals of 3.89 kg, 0.095 kg, and 0.282 kg of metal, plastic, and rubber, respectively, are available each day, how many components can be produced per day? (Round the final answer to nearest whole number.)

 

The solutions are c1 = __a__, c2 = __b__, and c3 = __c__.
worksheet.commonFeedback:

%media:formula37.mml%

clear, clc

%media:formula48.mml%

 

If F1 = 500 kg/h, yin = 0.1, F2 = 1000 kg/h, xin = 0, and K = 4, determine the values of yout and xout if a five-stage reactor is used. Note that equation (3) must be modified to account for the inflow weight fractions when applied to the first and last stages.

The values of yout = __a__ × 10–6 and xout = __b__ × 10–5.

%media:formula44.mml%

%media:formula45.mml%

%media:formula49.mml%

%media:formula50.mml%

 

The solution can be developed in a number of ways. For example, using a MATLAB script gives:

 

clear,clc,clf,format short g
F1=500;F2=1000;yin=0.1;xin=0;K=4;

r1=yin
rn=F2/F1*xin
pause
A=[diag super 0 0 0
sub diag super 0 0
     0 sub diag super 0
     0 0 sub diag super
     0 0 0 sub diag];
b=[r1 0 0 0 rn]';
Y=A\b
X=K*Y
Y=[yin Y'];
X=[X' xin];

worksheet.commonFeedback:
Using MATLAB gives,

Function

 

function [x, c] = YourLastName_Reactor(D, U, k, c0, cL, L, dx)
x=[0:dx:L]';
ns=L/dx-1;
A=zeros(ns);
b=zeros(ns,1);
A(1,1)=2*D/dx^2+k;A(1,2)=-(D/dx^2-U/2/dx);
b(1)=(D/dx^2+U/2/dx)*c0;
for i=2:ns-1
  A(i,i-1)=-(D/dx^2+U/2/dx);
  A(i,i)=2*D/dx^2+k;
  A(i,i+1)=-(D/dx^2-U/2/dx);
end
A(ns,ns-1)=-(D/dx^2+U/2/dx);
A(ns,ns)=2*D/dx^2+k;
b(ns)=(D/dx^2-U/2/dx)*cL;
c=A\b;
c=[c0;c;cL];

 

Script

 

clear,clc,clf

L=10;dx=0.5;D=2;U=1;k=0.2;c0=80;cL=20;

[x, c]=YourLastName_Reactor(D, U, k, c0, cL, L, dx);

plot(x,c,'-ok','LineWidth',2,...

    'MarkerSize',10,...

    'MarkerEdgeColor','k',...

function [x, y] = YourLastName_Beam(E, I, w, y0, yL, L, dx)
ns=L/dx-1;

worksheet.commonFeedback:
Using MATLAB

Function

 

function [x, T] = YourLastName_rod(hp, Tinf, T0, TL, L, dx)
ns=L/dx-1;
x=[dx:dx:L-dx]';
% set up system of equations
A=zeros(ns); b=zeros(ns,1);
A(1,1)=2+hp*dx^2;A(1,2)=-1;
b(1)=hp*dx^2*Tinf+T0;
for i=2:ns-1
  A(i,i-1)=-1; A(i,i)=2+hp*dx^2; A(i,i+1)=-1;
  b(i)=hp*dx^2*Tinf;
end
A(ns,ns-1)=-1; A(ns,ns)=2+hp*dx^2;
b(ns)= hp*dx^2*Tinf+TL;
% solve the system
T=A\b;
x=[0;x;L]; T=[T0;T;TL];

clear,clc,clf

L=12;dx=0.5;hp=0.0425;Tinf=220;T0=320;TL=450;

[x, y]= YourLastName_rod(hp, Tinf, T0, TL, L, dx)

plot(x,y,'-ok','LineWidth',2,...
